<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870424-0120 </DOCNO><HL> Consolidated Oil andamp; GasTo Restructure Debt</HL><DD> 04/24/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> CGS CPSBANKRUPTCIES (BCY) </IN><DATELINE> DENVER  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Consolidated Oil andamp; Gas Inc. said it reached an agreement in principle to restructure and modify $40.5 million in bank debt for it and its Columbus Energy Corp. unit.    Harry A. Trueblood Jr., chairman and president, told shareholders at the annual meeting that barring another collapse of energy prices -- which he no longer expects -- it appears the revised debt repayment schedules will escalate in a manner similar to expected energy price recoveries between now and 1993. Consolidated said it reached the agreement with Pittsburgh-based Mellon Bank Corp.    Separately, Consolidated Energy Partners L.P. said its majority-owned Consolidated Operating Partner L.P. expects to present a reorganization plan in about 45 days and hopes to emerge from Chapter 11 protection from creditors by year's end.    The partnership filed for protection from creditor lawsuits in March after missing a loan payment to two of its lenders, First Interstate Bank of California, a First Interstate Bancorp unit, and RepublicBank Dallas, a unit of RepublicBank Corp. </TEXT></DOC>